,Recommended,285310,11011761,"Posted: 1 July, 2014",all,lovinglife139,"Where to begin? RollerCoaster Tycoon is arguably the best tycoon game of all time. The game's development was mostly credited to only one man (Chris Sawyer), and was released in 1999. There were four games that defined my childhood. The Sims, Age of Empires II, Dungeon Keeper 2, and this.RollerCoaster Tycoon truly gives you the power to make exactly the kind of amusement park you want to build. Even in the scenarios, it largely feels like a free building game; the game does not ask you to do anything you don't want to do. For example, instead of asking you to build a park based on nothing but rollercoasters like some games might have implemented, Rollercoaster Tycoon simply plops you down on a plot of land and basically says, ""Get this many guests and have a good park rating in three years. Have fun and buh-bye!"" This game should be truly applauded for being a tycoon game that is not only great fun, but never turns into a chore by forcing you into situations where you feel you're only doing something to beat a level. It gives you an end goal, and it's up to you, the player, to decide exactly how you'll get there.The game allows you to build your own rollercoaster, water slide, log flume, monorail, railroad (and many more) designs from scratch, which gives you endless possibilities in each level (and you will be playing levels over and over again simply for the fun of doing them multiple ways). You can build these rides around one another, underground, over water...there are few limitations. You can also decide what color themes each ride has (or not), even down to making each car in a rollercoaster train a different color. Also, put shops and food stalls around your park and decide how much to charge. You can even charge for guests to use the bathroom, bringing out the greedy capitalist in each of us (I usually make a profit over running costs with my bathrooms, charging just $0.10 per visit).You can even name guests and track them, which brings another level of fun to an already ridiculously great game. Read a guest's thoughts, pick him up and drop him in front of a ride you think he'll like, see what things he's bought from your park that are in his inventory. Hey, you can even drop him in a lake if he's so angry he's potentially messing with your park rating and drown him. It's up to you!RollerCoaster Tycoon is also, in my opinion, better than its sequels. Other than some rides not being available in some levels, it will never revoke your abilities. In RollerCoaster Tycoon 2, there were levels where you had to meet a scenario goal without charging any entry fee for your park, for example, which only ended up taking freedom from the player's hands while pushing itself into the ""chore tycoon"" category. RollerCoaster Tycoon never crosses that line.In summary, RollerCoaster Tycoon is a fantastic classic game that is perfect as it is. While the graphics may be simplistic by today's standards, it would be simply ignorant to pass up the game because of it. This game is fun, relaxing, rewarding, timeless, and close to flawless. If you don't yet own this game, pick it up. Otherwise, the only one who is missing out is you. ;)"
,Recommended,285310,22629056,"Posted: 25 April, 2016",all,Microsoft Word,This and RCT2 are still some of the best games I ever played. Just can't beat it.
,Recommended,285310,19574735,"Posted: 8 December, 2015",all,Monsieur Bébé™,"For a game that was released over 15 years ago, it's amazing to still have such an impact on a gaming community and still be entertaining. I can't think of many other games that people actually still play on a daily basis because it's still as fun as it was released so many years ago and also able to compete with today's similar games. I can only hope that the new coming RCT World will be worthy of stepping in the footsteps of this magnificent game."
76561197973129601,Recommended,285310,31281981,Posted: 21 April,all,StefanWB,"The parts of RCT that have aged poorly:-- The visuals-- The audio quality-- The UI and menus-- The animations (which were gorgeous for their time btw)-- Just about everything that has to do with how the game looks.The parts of RCT that have aged extremely well:-- Building roller coasters is still a blast, with simple controls and lots of trial and error that legitimately pays off.-- The management part of the game is still brilliant and engrossing.-- The variety of maps and scenarios means hours of content.-- Plenty of options for personalising your park.-- Picking up customers who complain and dropping them in the water to drown them, or making them go on an unfinished or otherwise dangerous ride so they crash to their death, is still morbidly satisfying.-- Just about everything that has to do with how the game feels.In short, an immense amount of nostalgia and happy memories of playing RCT is what led me to buying and playing this in 2016. The fact that the game is still a ton of fun is what led me to play it for more than 100 happy hours in 2016. This is one of the best simulation/management games ever made, and THE definitive amusement park game, and it's a testament to its greatness that unlike many dinosaurs of turn-of-the-century PC gaming, it's still great today."
,Recommended,285310,15847821,"Posted: 15 May, 2015",all,Leadx[NL],"Rollercoaster Tycoon: Deluxe is a classic. A classic that I grew up with, and was amongst the very first games I've played in my life, so it was an instant buy for me, alongside RCT2.Here, like the games after it, you manage a theme park, and try to keep the rating as high as possible, and basically keep your visitors happy. (And if you so wish drown those who don't like your park, just to set an example)It's a fairly simple, and straight forward game that you can sink many, many hours into trying to manage your park, create the ultimate rollercoasters, and keep profit up at the same time.This game, unlike it's successor Rollercoaster Tycoon 2, has unlockable scenario's. You start with several scenario's, and work your way up (or down) from that, trying to get to the very bottom of the list. There's three lists of unlockable scenario's. One for the vanilla game, and the other two are from the expansions Corkscrew Follies and Loopy Landscapes, so if you're a completionist; you'll be sinking many, many hours into it!Other than that, the game has aged very well since when it was released back in 1999. So do you like managing parks, creating rollercoasters, completing scenario's to progress and having countless of hours of fun? Then throw your money at the screen and buy this game already!I give this game a definite 9/10, truly a wonderous game!"
