,Recommended,285310,28036909,"Posted: 29 November, 2016",all,Jessbee,"I played this when I was 7, and it's still very good. Enough said.In all seriousness, nostalgia does cloud our perception, and I don't play a lot of simulation games, so I may not be the best person to review this game since I don't have much to compare it to. I haven't played more than a few minutes of the sequels and games by other companies inspired by the series like Planet Coaster. Those are probably a better option if you're looking for a modern experience, as this game definitely is a bit dated. Still, for its age, I don't feel that the UI is too clunky or the learning curve is too steep. Fun to pick up for a couple hours exactly once, or to dump days into, if you have that kind of time.I never did fully understand a lot of the roller coaster-specific mechanics, like intensity and excitement, which can be limiting when I'm trying to make a park the best it can be. The track builder is a bit clunky, too. Still, I'm a lot better at the budgeting and management aspects than I was when I was a kid, and the game can still be easy or challenging depending on the scenario. The quirks and flaws are a drop in the bucket of nostalgic goodness. Or lake. Lake of goodness, which your guests can fall into and drown."
,Recommended,285310,26797221,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Jacobmeister,"RCT1 is a pretty big nostalgia trip - I picked it up 13 years ago off a family friend, got hooked pretty instantly. I remember extremely enjoying the first scenario.The game still runs without a problem for me on my computer (which has windows 10) although I have resolution issues on my higher def. laptop. (1920x1080 screen for my laptop, but 1280x768 monitor for my computer). Honestly though, I'm amazed it still runs at all, seeing how old it is.Obviously there's a few issues with the game; the inevitable station brakes failure, handymen automatically mow grass when you hire them (and their pathing is just AWFUL), no banked cornered hills / drops, everyone is extremely stingy with spending money on rides once they get a few months old... I don't care, it's still a great game. The scenarios are really easy, and pretty fun to replay on a semi-regular basis honestly.RCT2 is technically way better, but this is the OG. This started it all. If you love this, I'd recommend also getting OpenRCT2 and trying out playing with others online. Oh yes, that's a thing. And you can play the old scenarios on there too. But if you're getting this game, it's for the nostalgia anyway, and you can't not get it."
