,Recommended,285310,18873418,"Posted: 4 November, 2015",all,Pizza Time,"Such a nostalgia trip~Definitely still holds up as an easy building/management game that's great for all ages, beginners and experts alike. There's a lot of fun to be had starting up a little park then watching it grow slowly over time as you add stalls and rides and even build your own roller coasters. I absolutely love this game and remember playing it a lot as a kid (I still have the CD laying around, but I may or may not have lost it) and its sequel RollerCoaster Tycoon 2 adds to the experience in so many lovely ways~But since I played RCT1 much, much more than 2, I have to say that this is my favorite entry to the series with the second game nearly tying. RCT 3 was an interesting jump into 3D that added quite a bit and changed things up, but you can just never beat a classic~ Plus this game works on almost any computer due to its 2D nature and sprite-art, so I'm sure it'd work on a toaster if you had the right OS.Buy the game if you like management genres, but don't expect the deepest of intricacies."
,Recommended,285310,18883681,"Posted: 4 November, 2015",all,tm,"this game has enough nostalgia to make me sit at the title screen and listen to the theme music for a good 10-15 seconds before i actually play. my childhood and stuff. when i do play it, i play it for 3 hours straight or not at all. part of this is because you can't speed up the time scale of the game (it's old school or something), but mostly i just get lost for 20 minutes building a single rollercoaster because that♥♥♥♥♥♥i hard. the game also doesn't have steam overlay (♥♥♥♥ing 1999 man) so i have to minimize it to check the time on my computer, which means i have no awareness of time passage.it's really good though. the nostalgia is validated by the impressive content and detail that is in the game. the detail adds a lot of realism and interesting mechanics. building coasters, for example, that scare your customers on sight won't have much business and a coaster that inches along the track at speeds an agoraphobic wouldn't be intimidated by won't bring customers either. the content includes a big variety of rides, many of which aren't rollercoasters (half of the rides probably are roller coasters though). there are water rides, gentle rides like merry-go-rounds, thrill rides like swinging ships, and a variety of shops and stalls. the incorporation of many different elements creates a genuine experience of running a themepark.the game comes with something like 100+ scenarios; they are like campaigns with specific goals, such as reaching a certain company value at the end of october (it's always october for some reason) in year x. the scenarios are pretty difficult and time consuming. given the content, you can spend immense amounts of time working through those alone. not too bad for isometric 1999."
